<h2 id="introduction">Introduction</h2>

<p>One of the great strengths of computer programs is that they can process an incredible amount of information far faster than we could do it manually. To achieve this we need to be able to loop through collections and sequences. In this hands-on lab, weâ€™ll work through the popular interviewing Fizz-Buzz problem by creating a script that will prompt the user for the number of items to process, and then print out either the number, â€œFizzâ€, â€œBuzzâ€, or â€œFizzBuzzâ€ for each number between 1 and the user-provided number.</p>

<p>To feel comfortable completing this lab youâ€™ll want to know how to do the following:</p>

<p>Utilize for loops. Watch â€œThe for Loopâ€ video from the Certified Entry-Level Python Programmer Certification course.
Nest conditionals and loops. Watch the â€œNesting Loops and Conditionalsâ€ video from the Certified Entry-Level Python Programmer Certification course.
Utilize the range type. Watch â€œUsing rangeâ€ video from the Certified Entry-Level Python Programmer Certification course.</p>

<h2 id="the-scenario">The Scenario</h2>

<p>A typical Fizz-Buzz problem goes like this:</p>

<p>Write a program that prints the numbers from 1 - 100. For each multiple of three print â€œFizzâ€ instead of the number. For multiples of five print â€œBuzzâ€ instead of the number. If a number is a multiple of three and five then print â€œFizzBuzzâ€. Solving this problem requires two key components: looping and conditionals.</p>

<p>Weâ€™re going to write a script that prompts the user for the number of items to process (starting with 1). For each number, weâ€™ll print either â€œFizzâ€, â€œBuzzâ€, â€œFizzBuzzâ€, or the number. The criteria for what to print is:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Print â€œFizzBuzzâ€ if the number is divisible by 3 and 5.</li>
  <li>Print â€œFizzâ€ if the number is divisible by 3.</li>
  <li>Print â€œBuzzâ€ if the number is divisible by 5.</li>
  <li>Otherwise print the number.</li>
</ul>

<p>Hereâ€™s how the final script should work:</p>

